Killer Tune gets really good support with the 3 extra names and Harmonia, feels pretty nice to cut down on a few tuners now that we have another maindeck name even if "Encore"(Rotary) can't actually turn 0 with "Clip", because of that it still feels valuable to make use of "Belle" and "Mourner" in order to make "Crackle" who I have to assume will get banned eventually, this card makes "Clip" a generic-ish handtrap that can basically just kill some decks if it triggers on their turn.
"Nibiru" might be worth maindecking if leaning heavily into "Crackle" as it would allow you to clear your summon and banish 5 extra names
I expect "Clip" and "Crackle" to become common generic handtraps in a wide range of decks similar to how K9-17 Izuna is, this hasn't really been talked about by alot of people yet but feels very likely as a sideboard card atleast.

Vampires is a deck that uses it's Main Deck as a toolbox unlike most decks which mainly use the ED as their toolbox.

The reason why it's okay to play so many one ofs is because there are more than enough ways to search the pieces.

Solitaire can special summon Uni-Zombie which can either mill Familiar or Retainer which essentially means that you can very easily search any Vampire Spell/Trap or Monster.

 

The biggest problem this deck has is that each time you summon one of the smaller vampires from the GY you lose cards so you need a critical amount of Vampire cards in your starting hand. Vampire Ghost as an example is a very strong card however you need more Vampire monsters for it to even work + any disruption will often stop you right in your tracks.

 

The going 2nd cards E-Con and Change of Heart work in a very unique way in Vampires because their rank 6 and rank 8 can just use your opponents monsters as if they were the correct level to summon them and those 2 + your Link monsters are going to be your win condition because they enable OTKs

 

The Synchros are just another toolbox that can come up from time to time but they obv aren't the main focus of the deck, the focus is stealing your opponents monsters and use it to make XYZ and Links.

 

Update:

 

Delta of Invitation is a Zombie support card that has been released after the posting my initial list.

It is a crazy card for Zombies in general and this also remains true for Vampires. 

The most obvious change is that the Eldlich line now allows to actually set up a better board turn 1.

In my testing I was not only able to put up more Link Material but even Synchro plays got easier especially with Gozuki.

 

There have been also some minor alterations to the deck but Delta of Invitation is the one that had the most Impact during play testing

deck_description: This deck aims to use "Spellbook of the Grand Circle" to produce 5 materials of monsters using the Charmers. From there, you can summon "Awakening of the Possessed - Nefariouser Archfiend" as one of your five materials to link off, and grab a Possessed spell/trap, though "Possessed Partnerships" will be your go-to. After that, you can make your choice of "D/D/D Wave High King Caesar" via the Fiendsmith line or "Number F0: Utopic Draco Future" via the Ghostrick engine. This is by no means a meta deck, but it should be fun to play for those who like the Charmers, even if the end board is a little lacking in Charmer monsters. Here's hoping that KONAMI decides to print some decent Charmer bosses in the future!

Skeleton for a Darklord deck with minimal non-engine. Heavier on the pure stuff including some lords one could easily opt out of like Tezcatlipoca and the like, but ya gotta respect the style. Anyhow, the BPRO support can get the ball rolling hard, quickly accruing resources in a fun manner, with Djehuty grabbing Gulgolet making Condemned & fetching Dance, to make Eveningstar to fetch Fallen Angel & Banishment to fetch Morningstar then double dip into Banishment with Eveningstar's effect to fetch a trap that pitches like Enchantment, so on the opp's turn activate Enchantment for interruption pitching Morningstar, then double dipping into Dance with Eveningstar to make The First Darklord using the discarded Morningstar to enable the boardwipe, and then be able to summon Morningstar via Fallen Angel.

Alts include additional copies of Morningstar, other Darklords that can now be more easily summoned via Fallen Angel that have neat effects, more forbidden spells or Darklord traps, milling, drawing, fetching, and Super Poly along with its associated suite in case of feeling nasty.
The deck could include Dominus Impulse, mayyybe Diviner?, Mutiny in the Sky, Duality has a few neat options to flip into like Schuberta & Etoile, Augoeides and Fs for Arc Light.
Alongside Guardian Chimera, one can also probably fit in Knightlord Parshath, A Bao A Qu, Lahamu and Agent Moon.  

Additionally regarding hybrid builds, a Power Patron package can fit given that Terminus can fetch dark fairies, and Shaddolls can dump darks monsters straight from the deck while making fusions. There's a small engine of playset Dawn Angel Kambi with one Trickstar Nightshade and one Trickstar Colchica to eat up the normal summon and lead to a link 2. Photon Jumper plus a few copies of Galaxy Journey for similar function to Fallen Angel,

deck_name: Artmage Genesys w. E-HERO Prisma [Alinos Gateway FEB 2026]
deck_excerpt: Thumbnail for clout, this guy never came up lol.
deck_description:
Featured in the Alinos Gateway Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel Monthly for February 2026. VOD

Update on last month's Artmage list, dropping the Utopia package for A Hero Lives/Prisma and changing some pointed cards out to slot in the smiling green man. Went back to including Cartesia for Granguignol and Luluwalilith, and Vallon's finally out in Master Duel! Didn't come up for this Monthly by Arc Rebellion has still been able to steal games when running this build on ladder.

Added Mask of Restrict to the sideboard to hate out Nekroz and at worst discard to Artmage Academy. Upped Breakthrough Skill as it gets set up for free when discarded off Artmage Academy. Should consider Soundproofing if Synchros are now entering our little meta though.

deck_excerpt: All hail the queen of Dice Rally - Sky Striker Ace Raye!!!
deck_description:
All hail the undisputed queen of Dice Rally - Sky Striker Ace Raye!!!

Playing the 2026 February Dice Rally, I thought I could get away with blind second playing Rogue decks like Gren Maju and Ancient Gear - but I found that there were some incredibly powerful decks that make nigh-impenetreble boards like White Forest, Blue Eyes and Live Twins! So I thought I needed something with a bit more... FIRE POWER! Time to break dust off the good ol' reliable blind second Sky Striker!

With Dice Rally's only change to the Sky Striker arsenel with Widow Anchor at 1, the strategy is essentially full power! And that's in the lower power meta of Dice Rally where many meta decks like K9 and Dracotail and banned into oblivion, so Raye can run rampant and rampage her way through every board, every deck and every gamestate with blind second tools! 

This incredible power the Raye offers and the favourable conditions of the Dice Rally meta only leave it to the individual pilot's skill playing Sky Striker. Can you strike from the skies with the full power of an ace and dominate Dice Rally? 

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: FTK with Bishbaalkin enhanced with the addition of the GMX archetype.
deck_description:
Finally, I managed to make Bishbaalkin's FTK work with the fewest possible bricks, that is, without using Scrap Golem. To make this happen, the key card that must be added to the extra deck is Puzzlomino.

It can manipulate a monster's level to 5, and also has a second excellent effect of destroying cards on the field. It can trigger Lost World to protect normal monsters on the field and bring Doodle Beast - Stego to the field or send it to the gy to perform Reborn with the GMX fusion monster.

There's also a version with even fewer bricks, where you don't need to activate Lost World from the deck with Horned Saurus and use the level 5 Stego; you simply perform a level 5 Synchro instead.

The difference is that this version is super fragile against hand traps. Since you don't perform the Evolzar Dolkka before the combo goes to Bishbaalkin, any interaction from the opponent will prevent your FTK from working.

This deck is interesting to see how it works, the use of Puzzlomino is pretty cool, but I don't see any appeal to it, other than being a strategy to use when you go first. I would use all 9 GMX cards in the side deck, along with the extra deck bricks, which are Bishbaalkin, Number 33: Chronomaly Machu Mech and Puzzlomino, the Drop-n-Deleter, and put the 12 tech cards from the side deck in the main deck.

Then only when I go first, I would change the main deck to the GMX cards and focus on making the FTK happen. The interesting thing is that the real bricks of the deck are in the extra deck, and even having the bricks there, you still manage to have space for about 8 standard Dinosaur cards that you normally use in the deck's combo.

It's this ability of the deck to be both a standard Dinosaur deck, or a very consistent FTK deck, and that, in the worst case if the FTK doesn't happen, you get the standard Dinosaur endboard, that makes it interesting to use.

In the end, I see it as a deck for fun because Mulcharmy Fuwalos makes using Dinosaur FTK practically unfeasible, given the number of draws you'll give to the opponent, and the fact that the deck is super sensitive to hand traps as well, without many extenders available.

 

Test Hands

Below I will leave the test hands that exemplify how the FTK should be done: [insert link continuation on the duelingbook dot com / website]

 

Combo 1: FTK using Kaitoptera to make Horned Saurus and activate Lost World from the deck.

 

replay?id=813757-78562406

 

This is the only combo that can play around hand traps from the start because you make Dolkka and then Lost World protects against card targeting.

But it requires using bricks like Polymerization and Doodle Beast - Stego, which you can remove in the other combos I'll show.

Another detail in this combo is the fact that it uses Lost World: you need to put 9 monsters on the field for it to work, since Lost World reduces Bishbaalkin's ATK by 500 points, with only 8 monsters the FTK won't work.

 

Combo 2: FTK using GMX cards instead of Kaitoptera to make Bishbaalkin

You end up using fewer bricks in the main deck, but you have no protection against hand traps.

 

replay?id=813757-78577411

 

One detail at the end of the combo is that you didn't even need to use GMX Experiment #55; you can banish any card from your hand and bring Oviraptor to the field with Dark Dimension Soldier, which would already solve the issue of the 8th monster on the field for the FTK to happen.

That said, it doesn't matter whether you bring Researcher or Miscellaneousaurus with GMX Allos to have follow-up in the GY; either one ends up in the same place.

 

Combo 3: Ground Xeno + Petiteranodon + random card in hand

 

replay?id=813757-78979626

 

Combo using GMX cards to get to Bishbaalkin and Dark Dimension Soldier at the end to bring Oviraptor and have 8 monsters on the field for the FTK to work.

Notice that this combo has a sequence, first with Puzzlomino, then you make Geonator Transverser, which makes this combo line different from the common one.

 

Combo 4: Miscellaneousaurus + Petiteranodon + random card in hand

 

replay?id=813757-78979981

 

Combo without using either Kaitoptera or the GMX engine, just normal cards from the Dinosaur deck because Petiteranodon allows you to access Dogoran to make Bishbaalkin without using Double Evolution Pill.

This gives you the number of summons needed to FTK with 8 monsters on the field by using the effect of Dark Dimension Soldier and bringing Oviraptor to the field.

 

Decklist Choices

I like Knightmare Phoenix because I always want to have a quick answer for continuous floodgates that, despite finally going to the banlist, you still keep getting hit from time to time.

But ideally, you should use Knightmare Cerberus, which further increases the deck's 2-card combo combinations using Lost World, which is extremely necessary in a deck that needs to do 2-card combos to function. So much so that I changed it in the final decklist.

Another very important change I made was removing Kaitoptera, Polymerization, and Doodle Beast - Stego to replace them with 3x The Fallen & The Virtuous, and removing Horned Saurus from the extra deck to replace it with Albion the Branded Dragon.

This way, I can have 2 more card combos available in the deck, because I can use this card to destroy the Lost World token if needed.

In other words, I included all these cards to exemplify all the combo forms for the FTK, but ultimately I removed all the cards from the first combo with Kaitoptera because I have more bricks to make it work.

And I would also leave all 9 GMX cards in the side deck and only put them in when going first.

This way, my main deck would be 3x The Fallen & The Virtuous, 3x Ash Blossom, 3x Mulcharmy Purulia, and Mulcharmy Fuwalos.

In the extra deck, I would swap the cards so that the FTK also works for the side deck, which are Bishbaalkin, Number 33, and Puzzlomino for Dingirsu, Sabersaurus, and Little Knight. I would only put them in when I'm going to do the FTK first.

 

I hope you enjoyed this content.

deck_excerpt: Learn how to play Jurrac Ryu-Ge
deck_description:
Jurrac Ryu-Ge is the best version of Dinosaur for the current Yu-Gi-Oh! format, and the reason is simple: it has 18 one-card combo forms, half of which you still play around several hand traps, except for Fuwalos and Droll.

The versatility of this deck against hand traps is so good that you can afford to auto-droll & lock bird to prevent your opponent's Fuwalos from drawing cards. You even use Called By the Grave, Crossout Designator, and Ash Blossom just to prevent Fuwalos from ruining your life going first.

The Melody of Awakening Dragon is the best card in the deck; if your opponent doesn't ash blossom on this card, you've instantly won the game. The combo simply plays around all the hand traps, and Jurrac's endboard is extremely strong and resilient to board break.

The chance of you winning the game by going first and taking the endboard is almost 100%, considering you get 3 board wipes plus an omni negate and two summon inherent negates.

 

Decklist

This decklist shows that it's possible to use a large number of tech cards, at least 12 to 16 hand traps, or more if you want. It's a simple but functional deck and the best way to play Dinosaur in 2026.

I would say there's no other way to play Dinosaur competitively other than Jurrac. All other Dinosaur decks need to do a 2-card combo to work.

A cool detail is the addition of The Fallen & The Virtuous, which is excellent not only for going second, but also for going first if the opponent uses Veiler or Impermanence on Stego.

You chain The Fallen & The Virtuous to destroy Stego, and Stego, upon resolution of the chain link, will destroy The Fallen & The Virtuous itself to resolve its effect. Therefore, it becomes a way to avoid targeting cards and make your 1-card combo, Jurrac Stego, bypass common hand traps in the format.

You can also use Ryu-Ge's continuous spells/traps to play better against Mulcharmy Fuwalos; besides increasing the number of interactions, you can also recycle Mistva to your hand and have a better follow-up on your next turn.

Another detail is about the quick-play spell Ryu-Ge Rising; Ryu-Ge cards are weak against Droll & Lock Bird, so you need to use this card on turn 1, right in the draw phase, to avoid being punished by a Droll & Lock Bird.

 

Is it worth using the GMX archetype with Ryu-Ge Jurrac?

I tested using the deck with the new GMX archetype, but in this version, which has few Dinosaur cards, the excavated monsters will mostly not be good cards, since you can excavate Oviraptor or Stego, but apart from that, if you excavate the level 1 monsters in this deck, there's a high chance you won't be able to continue the combo.

I think the engine is already too big to add more potential bricks; it's better to just play Ryu-Ge Jurrac. Not to mention the fact that you would have to increase the deck's engine to 60 cards, which means there's a real chance you could lose the game by using the fusion spell Experiment #55 and excavating 20 cards.

Another negative point is that these cards have Light monsters in the engine, which means that Dominus Impulse will shut down the entire engine when used from the hand.

 

Test Hands: Place the continuation of the link on the duelingbook dot com / website

 

Combo 1: Jurrac Stego (Full Combo)

 

replay?id=813757-79006173

 

End Board: Jurrac Astero + Megalo /in GY: Jurrac Astero /in Hand: Oviraptor (Follow Up)

 

Note if you already have a follow-up: You could also have added the last Megalo from the deck to your hand with the Oviraptor, and use the Megalo's effect on the field to discard it and another card in your hand to draw 2 cards and find tech cards.

The difference is that in this case you don't have direct access to the 3 Astero, you use the first one and summon Meteor, and Meteor will be able to pop Megalo to send the third Astero to the GY.

In this combo, you don't need to reborn any tuner when making the first nuke, so if you have a Mulcharmy in hand, you can use it in the resolution with your board clear.

 

Combo 2: The Melody of Awakening Dragon + Stego combo with bricks in hand

 

replay?id=813757-78998209

 

End Board: Varudras + 2x Jurrac Astero + War Zone /in GY: Jurrac Astero /in Hand: Oviraptor (Follow Up) /in Extra Deck: Mistva (Follow Up)

 

In this combo, I could have simply added only the Mistva with the Awakening Dragon, thus being able to perform the combo normally. However, I realized after performing the combo that you can add up to 2 Dragons. So, know that when you have bricks in hand, you can add only one Dragon to your hand.

 

Combo 3: The Melody of Awakening Dragon + Stego (Full Combo)

 

replay?id=813757-78997839

 

End Board: Varudras + 2x Jurrac Astero + War Zone /in GY: Jurrac Astero /in Hand: Tyranno (Follow Up) /in Extra Deck: Mistva (Follow Up)

 

Detail: I made a small mistake at the beginning of the combo, which was using Mistva's effect without first putting Anva in the Pendulum Zone to protect it from hand traps. Don't forget to put Anva in the Pendulum Zone first before using any Ryu spell.

I also made a mistake using the second Megalo as fusion material, but I should have used Aeolo instead to destroy Megalo with Oviraptor and have an Astero in the GY.

 

Combo 4: Oviraptor + Megalo/Miscellaneousaurus

 

replay?id=813757-79009381

 

End Board: Astero + Megalo / in GY: Astero + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up)

 

Detail: If the combo is Oviraptor + Miscellaneousaurus, you end up banishing Miscellaneousaurus from the GY, so you don't have it as a follow-up. The result is the same, but worse for a follow-up.

Another point to consider is that you could have added Stego to your hand and special summoned Megalo to use its effect and discard Stego to the GY along with another card from your hand to draw two cards.

The issue here is that this play doesn't revolve around Droll & Lock Bird. Therefore, if you want to respect hand traps, it's safer to send Stego to the GY with Oviraptor.

 

Combo 5: Oviraptor + Aeolo + any random card

 

replay?id=813757-79275198

 

End Board: Oviraptor + Megalo /in GY: Astero + Aeolo /in Hand: 2 draws

 

This combo shows that even after drawing Aeolo, you can still get 2 Astero cards alive on your opponent's turn. Just add Megalo, Special Summon it from your hand and use its effect to discard Aeolo and another card, draw two cards, and use Oviraptor's second effect to reborn Aeolo from the GY while destroying Megalo on the field.

 

Combo 6: Jurrac Stego vs Nibiru

 

replay?id=813757-79007486

 

End Board: Giga-Cannon + Nibiru Token /in GY: Astero + Megalo /in Hand: Nothing

 

This combo shows that Nibiru isn't a problem for Jurrac's 1-card combo. The only difference here is that you don't have a follow-up in hand, but you can still get 2 Jurrac Astero in the GY normally.

I showed the use of the RANK-4 Giga-Cannon in this example, but if I had reborn the second Megalo, the result would also be the same.

 

Combo 7: Going Second combo using Stego + Miscellaneousaurus

 

replay?id=813757-79010036

 

End Board: Tyranno + Giga-Cannon /in GY: Astero + Megalo /in Hand: Nothing

 

Many decks don't have an answer for the Miscellaneousaurus effect in hand, so you can hard make a Synchro Summon of Meteor to board wipe the field and then deal 7k damage to your opponent, and on your opponent's turn you destroy the Giga-Cannon to deal the remaining 1k damage needed to win the game.

I decided to show this combo because many people don't realize it's possible to directly summon Meteor going second and clear the field.

 

Conclusion

In a game evolution where all decks that don't perform a 1-card combo have been excluded from the competitive scene, the traditional Dinosaur deck has been left behind.

Now that we have a 1-card combo with Stego and the Ryu Ge engine to protect the combo from hand traps, this is the best version of Dinosaur in years.

The Ryu Ge cards, in particular, can force opponent interactions by going second, not to mention the large number of good tech cards the deck can use to defend itself as well.

 

I hope you enjoyed this short article.

Complete guide to playing Jurrac in the Genesys format.
deck_description:
Jurrac in the Genesys format, as well as in the TCG, is the best version of Dinosaur. I personally think this Genesys format version is even cooler than the TCG version with Ryu Ge, considering that here you use the Ground Xeno engine to have access to a much better follow-up on turn 3, which is the deck's biggest weakness.

 

The combos are the same, with the difference being that you can use Drillygnathus to recycle Miscellaneousaurus back to the GY, and you can also return the vanilla level 6 to the deck, which makes Xeno Meteorus excellent on the next turn for an OTK.

 

You simply reborn it with Meteor, and on the next turn you use Miscellaneousaurus in the GY to bring Baby or Petit from the deck, pop it with the Meteorus effect to bring the vanilla back, and bring Oviraptor from the deck to add Tyranno to your hand.

 

You have the option of using Oviraptor to destroy the Vanilla monster and reborn Aeolo, and Aeolo brings Stego back to the field. Here you will have 2 level 4 and one level 6 tuner, you can make Chengying and then use Stego's effect to send the second Tyranno from the deck to the GY and bring Titano along with the last Megalo from the deck.

 

This Titano can use its effect to gain 1000 ATK just to trigger the effect of Chengying and banish 1 card from the opponent's field and GY, and there's still Tyranno that will come from the hand to finish the game, plus you can make another Astero if there are any left in the extra deck.

 

That's why it's interesting to do the combo without using the 3 Megalo from the deck if possible. It is because of this excellent follow-up that these cards provide, that I consider it a good deck for the Genesys format.

 

The Xeno Meteorus engine is so flexible that you could have added the baby or Petit instead of Oviraptor and normal summoned it, used Meteorus's effect to pop it and summon Vanilla lv6, then summon another baby or Petit and use the second effect of the Oviraptor to destroy and bring out an Aeolo and bring out a Pankratops from the deck, for example. This way you end up with an XYZ lv6 and another XYZ lv4, plus a boss monster like Pankratops.

 

The end board it makes is very good against blind second cards, and considering that in the Genesis format few decks can use many hand traps, you have a great chance of getting your combo through and making an end board resilient to tech cards.

 

Decklist

 

Jurrac's decklist is almost 100% focused on the deck's engine, although some engine cards work well going second, such as Pankratops, Dogoran, and

Miscellaneousaurus, which makes dinosaur monsters unaffected during the main phase.

 

You combine that with the 3 Small Worlds to add Miscellaneousaurus to your hand, making the deck decent going second because it has many cards that the opponent needs to have quick, immediate answers for.

 

Not to mention that the extra deck has Chengying, a very good Synchro that you can make even over the Xeno Meteorus lock, before locking onto Dinosaur after using Stego's effect.

 

Double Evolution Pill is another way to follow up on turn 3, because basically your turn 1 combo just sends Dinosaurs to the GY, but you can easily get past that with an Evolzar on the field that you'll have in the GY on turn 3.

 

There's also the fact that it's not good to summon Tyranno to the field, considering that it will be destroyed by Meteor on your opponent's turn, so if you have Tyranno in your hand, keep it for your next turn.

 

Small World is three more copies of Miscellaneousaurus in the deck, literally any monster in the deck can be transformed into it, making Small World a tech card going second, because you simply add Misc and use the effect to protect the Dinos during the main phase.

 

The easiest card to remove from this decklist is certainly Sabersaurus, but with the addition of the GMX cards to the deck, it becomes useful for some specific combos that I'll show later.

 

Test Hands: Only Jurrac Dino, GMX cards will be covered in the next topic.

[Insert link continuation on duelingbook dot com /]

 

Important information: many of the following combos I would replace Jurrac Volcano with Jurrac Impact because it's more versatile against the opponent, so always analyze what's best to set with Astero's effect.

 

Combo 0: Showing some Small World combinations to add Miscellaneousaurus

 

replay?id=813757-79038289

Basically any monster + Small World = Miscellaneousaurus, it replaces Fossil Dig in the deck.

 

Combo 1: Jurrac Stego (1 card Full Combo)

 

replay?id=813757-79029380

End Board: Astero + Drillygnathu + Volcano + Impact /in GY: 2x Astero + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up) /in Hand: Double Evolution Pill (Follow Up)

 

Combo 2: Ground Xeno + Babycerasaurus

 

replay?id=813757-79031512

End Board: Astero + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero + Megalo + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up) /in Hand: Double Evolution Pill (Follow Up)

 

In this combo, you use both of Oviraptor's effects right at the start, so you don't need to use Miscellaneousaurus's effect in the GY; leave it there as a follow-up.

 

It's cool that you use Stego to send Petiteranodon to the GY and summon two Level 1 Jurrac monsters. This shows that not all combos require sending a Level 4 monster; some combos allow you to send a Level 2 monster instead.

 

Combo 3: Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus

 

replay?id=813757-79034759

End Board: Astero + Drillygnathu + Volcano / in GY: Astero + Megalo + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up) / in Hand: Double Evolution Pill (Follow Up)

 

This combo is done using Tyranno to summon Megalo and Titano from the deck to summon Astero with two monsters. There's also the clever play of destroying Giga-Cannon with Volcano to send an Astero to the GY.

 

Combo 4: Oviraptor + Petiteranodon

 

replay?id=813757-79034191

End Board: Astero + Drillygnathu + Volcano /in GY: Astero + Megalo + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up) /in Hand: Double Evolution Pill (Follow Up)

 

In this combo, I sent Tyranno again with Stego's effect and special summoned a level 1 + level 9 Titano from the deck to summon Jurrac Astero.

 

Then I summon Giga-Cannon to destroy Volcano with the field and be able to summon Megalo from the deck just to destroy it immediately with Giga-Cannon, deal 1k damage to the opponent and send the second Astero to the GY.

And since you can access the third Astero starting with two, this combo, despite not accessing the Impact trap, gives you at least 3 Astero in one turn.

 

Jurrac GMX in Genesys format

 

Learn below how you can use GMX cards to your advantage to get more 1-card combos with Dinosaur cards, since Oviraptor becomes a possible 1-card combo, Miscellaneousaurus too, and GMX Researcher is practically a second Oviraptor for Normal Summon with several possible 1-card combos.

 

Combo 1: GMX Researcher (1 card combo = excavate any Jurrac level 1 monster)

 

replay?id=813757-79249824

End Board: 2x Astero + Drillygnathus + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up) + Xeno Meteorus (Follow Up)

 

Combo 2: GMX Researcher (1 card combo = excavate Oviraptor)

 

replay?id=813757-79253617

End Board: Astero + Volcano + Impact /in GY: 2x Astero

You use Oviraptor to add Megalo to your hand and summon Astero.

 

Combo 3: GMX Researcher (1 card combo = excavate Miscellaneousaurus)

 

replay?id=813757-79253836

End Board: Astero + Giga-Cannon (Miscellaneousaurus material follow-up) + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero

 

After summoning Stego with Volcano, send Tyranno to the GY to bring Titano and Megalo from the deck and summon the second Astero.

 

Combo 4: GMX Researcher (1 card combo = excavate Stego)

 

replay?id=813757-79254950

End Board: Astero + Stego + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero

 

Stego sends Tyranno, brings Titano and Megalo to access Astero. Then it's simple to summon the second Astero to set the trap card Impact.

 

Combo 5: Oviraptor (1 card combo = excavate any Jurrac lv1 monster)

 

replay?id=813757-79244992

End Board: 2x Astero + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero

 

Combo 6: Oviraptor (1 card combo = excavate Petiteranodon)

 

replay?id=813757-79245659

End Board: Astero + Megalo + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero + Xeno Meteorus (Follow Up)

 

This combo is quite interesting because in the Genesys format you can't use Link Monsters, so you do the other GMX Fusion with Velox to get Dinosaur in the GY and use the second effect of Oviraptor to pop Petiteranodon and summon Xeno Meteorus from the deck to make Astero.

 

And with Stego I even sent another Baby Cerasaurus and just summoned 2 Jurrac lv1 to make the second Astero and finish the end board.

 

Combo 7: Oviraptor (1 card combo = excavate Babycerasaurus)

 

replay?id=813757-79245785

End Board: Astero + Velox + Volcano /in GY: Astero + Megalo

 

Here you have to use Stego effect to send Tyranno and summon Titano and Aeolo to make the first Astero. Then you make the Giga-Cannon to destroy with Volcano and manage to send the second Astero to the GY.

 

Combo 8: Oviraptor (1 card combo = excavate Xeno Meteorus)

 

replay?id=813757-79254618

End Board: Astero + Megalo + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero

 

You use Stego's effect to send Babycerasaurus and summon Aeolo and Megalo from the deck, make the second Astero, and keep Megalo on the field to send the third Astero to the GY on your opponent's turn.

 

Combo 9: Oviraptor (1 card combo = excavate Stego)

 

replay?id=813757-79255085

End Board: Astero + Giga-Cannon + Volcano /in GY: Astero + Megalo

 

Use Stego to send Babycerasaurus to the GY and bring a Megalo and an Aeolo from the deck to make Astero.

 

Combo 10: Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus + Double Evolution Pill (can’t summon Archosaur because I only play 1 Pill)

There are 3 different versions, see below:

 

Combo 10.1 - Version that ends with the Impact trap set, best possible end board.

 

replay?id=813757-79252744

End Board: 2x Astero + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up)

 

The cool thing about this combo is the use of RANK-4 Sabersaurus to destroy the Babycerasaurus from your hand and summon a level 1 Jurrac from the deck, which allows you to end the field with the Jurrac trap set.

 

Detail: it's optional to use the Double Evolution Pill here to bring out Titano and make the third Astero; you could have kept it in your hand as a follow-up.

 

Combo 10.2 - Optimized version, but with the Impact trap set, with access to all 3 Asteros

Detail: It doesn't matter if it was Petiteranodon instead of Babycerasaurus, the combo would be the same.

 

replay?id=813757-79249190

End Board: 2x Astero + Stego + Volcano + Impact /in GY: Astero + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up)

 

You destroy Babycerasaurus and access Jurrac Stego to continue the combo. You need to use Stego to send another Babycerasaurus to the GY and summon 2 level 1 Jurracs.

 

The difference here is that you use Volcano to destroy Megalo and summon another Megalo from the deck to use Double Evolution Pill and bring Titano from the deck to access the last Astero and set the Impact trap.

 

Combo 10.3 - The same version as 10.2, but it doesn't end with the Impact trap set because you only play 1 Astero

 

replay?id=813757-79248737

End Board: Astero + Giga-Cannon + Volcano /in GY: Astero + Megalo + Miscellaneousaurus (Follow Up) /in Hand: Evolution Pill (Follow Up)

 

This version is also interesting because you pass with the Giga-Cannon on the field, which means that when you use the first Astero, you can trigger the effect of Megalo in sequence and send the third Astero to the GY, but I still prefer to end with the trap set, so I would do combo 10.2.

 

Cool deck synergies

 

Jurrac Titano isn't just a vanilla card on the field; its effect of banishing a Jurrac and gaining 1k ATK is useful for triggering the effect of Chengying. Furthermore, you can loop Dogoran back to your hand with Stego, as it has a secret effect that, when destroyed by battle, bounces a face-up card from the field to your hand.

 

With this, you can use Dogoran twice in the turn, allowing you to remove cards from your opponent without destroying them, preventing their float effects from being activated.

 

Now, cool cards in the deck are Giga-Cannon, which is useful when you're locked into Dinosaurs because of Stego. You play it and destroy it with some effect to destroy an opponent's card and inflict 1k burn damage.

 

This is very good for dealing with annoying cards, especially backrow while locked into Dinosaur. Sabersaurus is useful for untapping Tyranno that was flipped face-down by an opponent's Book of Moon card, which the Mimighoul deck does quite often.

 

Or to change the battle position of a weak opponent's monster to attack so you can deal a lot of damage with Tyranno attacking it, or even finish the game with a single attack from Drillygnathus while you don't have Xyz Material, since you destroy Sabersaurus to increase its ATK to 5k, and without Xyz Material it inflicts double damage, which is 10k damage, similar to the OTK of Double or Nothing! that Utopia decks do.

 

Finally, I want to talk about how a Babycerasaurus in hand is indeed a follow-up: if you only have an Aeolo on the field and a Babycerasaurus in your hand as a follow-up, you can simply tribute Aeolo and bring Stego back to the field, normal summon Babycerasaurus and destroy it with Stego's effect to bring Oviraptor from the deck and add Tyranno to your hand.

 

It turns out that Stego doesn't need to Special Summon a Jurrac monster from the deck or hand; you only need to have a Dinosaur monster in the deck to activate the effect, send a Dino to the GY, but you don't need to Special Summon it.

 

With this, you fix in your mind that Stego on turn 3 always has the effect of popping a living card, regardless of whether you have Jurrac in the deck to summon or not. The only downside to this play is that even without bringing a Jurrac from the deck, you are still locked into Dinosaur monsters for the rest of the turn, so the OTK must be done with Giga-Cannon.

 

Optimized Tricks and Plays

 

Jurrac Volcano isn't just a 1.5 card combo; if your combo doesn't succeed, it stays on the field and the opponent will have to play around it. Against Radiant Typhoon it's not good because it will always have MST to deal with the field spell, but against other decks this card is very good to use.

 

If you brick with Miscellaneousaurus just for the play, you can simply summon Megalo from the deck, destroy it in the End Phase, and send Astero to the GY to have at least 1 Meteor guaranteed on your opponent's turn.

 

In the Genesys format, you'll face many decks whose main hand trap is Ghost Ogre because it only costs 3 points, so always try to set a spell on the field when using Stego's effect. That way, if it's destroyed by Ghost Ogre, you can still destroy the spell on the field to continue your play.

 

Although, if you use Ghost Ogre in your deck, you can reborn with Meteor, and its effect will be alive because it can also be activated from the field.

 

Another detail of this deck is that you can always, during the combo, if you have any Jurrac brick in your hand like Aeolo or Impact, send it to the GY with another card from your hand and draw 2 cards.

 

I personally don't usually use Jurrac Volcano's effect to bring one from the deck during my combo, but if you want to remove a Stego from the deck to have better draws on the next turn, you can always use the field spell's effect for that purpose, considering that you've already played practically all the Jurracs to the GY, drawing another Stego isn't very strong on turn 3.

 

Conclusion

 

I think it's a very competent deck for the Genesys format, and I see it as better prepared to face the format's decks compared to the TCG, where you can use the Ryu Ge engine and have 12 more combo cards to use, but you have to deal with decks that have more space for tech cards, more consistency in making 1 combo cards, and that have an infinitely better grind game than Jurrac's.

 

Now in the Genesys format, the deck makes very good endboards, in addition to having more chances going second and managing to have excellent follow-ups on the next turn. But I don't consider it among the best decks in the format, since it needs many card combinations to play, and there are decks like Dracotail that can easily handle the endboard.

deck_excerpt: dracotail, magistus, invoked,branded, branded dracotail,dracotail branded.
deck_description: this is a super spicy list!! invoked branded dracotail magistus combined in one deck that has 9 interruptions combo!

So this fever dream requires explaining. 
First off, the Multiplication of Ants in the deck is a stand-in for Multiplying Kuriboh that is not this site yet.

The main goal of the deck is simple: beat your opponent with a giant Kuribabylon. The problem is that the archetype is quite inconsistent, so here's the thought process of fixing that. Linkslayer, Disablaster, Red Layer & Barox / Best Monster of 2017 (via Ready Fusion) are lvl 5s that can special summon themselves for free (with some conditions) and the maindecks can also be tribute summoned (to be the only thing on your field). The fives are important for enabling Five Star Twilight, which gets us all the gang on board. Kuribee is the searcher for the spell so it's empathic to have access to it, usually via Kuribah who can summon it directly off the deck (as does Multiplying). Kuribeh is not good but we need the names and the buff can occasionally be fun, if it comes to reviving some light kuriboh off Agnumday and then making it even bigger. The og is also not useful but for its name, and Kuriboo can also search another one, but brings it to hand only. Other than the five kuristars, we have Kuribohrn who can help wall with either effect (and is also a light fiend), Detonating helps wall and can be interruption, Rainbow is bad but is a name and a light fiend, Barokuriboh can search by destroying itself.

Now for the reason Kuribandit is in the deck, and the reason we're going for 60. Kuribabylon benefits off a full grave, both for the stats and its summoning condition, but I opted for some support, to make sure the games can close and there is an occasional turn-1 play other than "Set Bee, pass". As such, Mutiny in the Sky can live very easily through a combination of Bandit / Twilight & Reasoning / Grass, making primarily Luce (who triggers off Barok popping itself). There other side to this is the Fiendsmith engine, which can simply fuel the grave more with Tract being able to fetch Bohrn or Rainbow, but also making its own line, easily via Lurrie going for the Requiem for Lacrima for Engraver for Sequence for (usually) Desirae for Agnumday for either reviving and strapping Desirae with Requiem too, or per wacky occasion reviving a kuriboh for maximum mockery.
Maybe Lurrie can be omitted from the list to make the fiendsmith line less easy to access. Lastly for the main deck, Dystopia the Despondent is a classic, and where else can one summon an unsearchable 5k/5k with neary a worthwhile protection that even nerfs your board. Classic I say.

Regarding the rest of the extra deck, Necroquip Princess is another fusion for Mutiny or Sequence that can draw a card, Goddess after Twilight or Bohrn can help fix some mucky game states, while Saryuja after Twilight or Bohrn can dig for a card. S:P is invaluable, being able to banish herself to leave the field open to have a single lvl 5 on board for Twilight, Pentestag can help Babylon punch better. Linkuriboh can help walling, and Anima is jumpscare removal.

Regarding alternatives, Winged + Flute + LV6 provide more umph but I don't think are worth the space, Mystic Tomato can be a decent choice if the desire is for a much weaker list without the fusion aspects, Brown Magician can become lvl 5 but wants a deck heavier on spells (power spell board breaker version?), Ankuriboh is neat (?).
Sylvan Princessprite can "dig" for spells but can also become a giant space mech, the Knightmare trio is generic utility. Maybe cards like Dark Hole also fit for clearing the field for the 5s to drop. Tualatin is funny.

An entirely different version could be made with Sphere, Relinkuriboh , Relinquished & Millennium-Eyes Restrict.

I have been informed by an associate nutcase that there could be a line via Aerial Eater and Sangan to make the Fiendsmith act as a bridge for the Kuriboh side. While it sounds cool, I have been in the tank far too long already.

In case it wasn't obvious, there are not handtraps here, and the deck's power level is slightly above the floor, but hopefully it can be fun enough for people to try and / or experiment with it.

deck_excerpt: This deck plays like a chaotic carnival, packed with tricks, gambles, and reality-bending surprises.
deck_description:
This Yu-Gi-Oh deck plays like a chaotic carnival, packed with tricks, gambles, and reality-bending surprises. Its monsters are a quirky cast: Iron Dragon Tiamaton crashes the field when zones get crowded, Penguin Knight waddles in with nostalgic charm, Dice Jar turns every roll into a life-or-death gamble, Ceremonial Bell slows the duel with mystery, Parasite Paracide sneaks into the opponent’s deck, and Zany Zebra keeps targeting unpredictable. The spells twist the rules of the game itself—Chain Energy makes every move costly, Convulsion of Nature flips decks upside down, Ground Collapse locks zones, Terminal World slows summoning, Final Countdown sets a ticking clock to victory, Yu-Jo Friendship dares opponents to shake hands, and Inferno Tempest wipes the field after big damage. The traps are pure prankster tools: Lucky Punch is a slot machine of risk, D.D. Dynamite punishes banished cards, Exchange of the Spirit swaps graveyards for shock value, Magical Hats hides cards under illusions, Mystical Refpanel bounces effects back, Relay Soul keeps you alive at 0 LP, and Transmission Gear forces a mini coin-flip duel inside the duel. Altogether, this deck thrives on confusion, laughter, and outrageous wins—it’s less a straightforward strategy and more a funhouse of surprises where every card feels like a trick waiting to be sprung.

Deck Vibe: Chaos Carnival of Surprises

This deck is less about brute force and more about mind games, randomness, and hilarious twists. It’s like inviting your opponent to a carnival where every booth hides a trap, every dice roll could explode the game, and every card flip rewrites reality.

Monsters - The Oddball Cast

  • Iron Dragon Tiamaton → The heavy hitter who shows up when the field gets too crowded.
  • Penguin Knight → A nostalgic throwback, waddling in with cheeky charm.
  • Dice Jar → The ultimate gamble — one roll can swing life points wildly.
  • Ceremonial Bell → A peaceful guardian, slowing the pace and adding mystery.
  • Parasite Paracide → Sneaky little bug that invades your opponent’s deck.
  • Zany Zebra → The comic relief, messing with targeting and keeping things unpredictable.

Spells – Reality-Bending Rules

  • Chain Energy → Every move costs life points, turning the duel into a toll road.
  • Convulsion of Nature → Flip the deck upside down — literally!
  • Ground Collapse → Shuts down monster zones, cramping your opponent’s style.
  • Terminal World & NEXT → Slow the duel to a crawl, one summon at a time.
  • Final Countdown → The ticking clock win condition — survive 20 turns and victory is yours.
  • Yu-Jo Friendship → Shake hands with your opponent… if they dare!
  • Inferno Tempest → A fiery reset button that banishes everything after big damage.

Traps – The Prankster’s Toolbox

  • Lucky Punch → Risky rewards, like a slot machine in trap form.
  • D.D. Dynamite → Punishes banished cards with explosive damage.
  • Exchange of the Spirit → Swap graveyards for a shocking twist.
  • Magical Hats → Hide your cards under hats — a classic trickster move.
  • Mystical Refpanel → Redirect effects back at your opponent.
  • Relay Soul → Keeps you alive with one monster, even at 0 LP.
  • Transmission Gear → Forces a mini duel inside the duel with a coin toss battle.

Overall Personality

This deck is a chaotic funhouse: part prankster, part gambler, part survivalist. It thrives on confusing opponents, bending the rules of the game, and pulling off outrageous wins with cards that make people laugh, groan, or cheer.

deck_excerpt: First personal and fun deck that isn't a structure x 3 or a meta deck since I've been playing again.
deck_description: My first personal and fun deck that isn't a structure x 3 or a meta deck since I've been playing again, now in Genesys

Pure RA with the new support from Burst Protocol, this deck is still good, and the new support does help the deck, but this archetype wont't be getting any tops anytime soon unfortunately.

If OSS was ubanned I would almost certainly be playing it with 3 x Diabellstars and a small Snake Eye package. Because of this I am playing as many starters as I can to make sure we have something to do when the inevitable handtrap is activated. The pots are included in these as they can potentially dig for such starters, hence why I've included two of Arbitrator and Prom Prin as Prosp cost and to prevent Extrav stopping the main link play this deck goes for.

A well timed Nib still ruins this deck and droll can be played through but is also still a problem, hence why this deck isn't meta. We have evenly's and Purulia's in the side for going second and plenty of Solemn's for going first. As for Dominus restrictions, it's only non-engine that is restricted by activating from hand so keep that in mind, the extra is all dark and fire.

As for the new cards, Arbitrator is a good boss montser and allowing regular access to HQ is a massive bonus to this decks grind game, you may even consider playing two HQ to benefit from this in grinds. I just wish it did anything on destruction of itself to really gel it together with the Prom Prin you would have used to link climb to it. Quick Attacker is also useful as an extra starter although its annoying that it locks you into fire ED monsters. It would be nice if it had quick effects as it effects but I understand that RA Impulse is already fulfilling that niche for the deck. It would be nice if both cards did a bit more but they're still good additions and Blazing Dominion should give this deck some moreuseful cards.

Lastly this deck is probably better when accompanied with some popular engines. The most obvious and simplest to run is Fiendsmith which was great while Moon was legal but is less consistent now, runnable but nothing ground breaking. The more interesting engine I've seen used is an Azamina one to give the deck an omni-negate in Illia Silvia so I'd go for that one if you desire a side-engine to RA. Neither of these options will make the deck competitive in the current meta, but the deck can still compete at the local and potentially regional level as well.

deck_name: Exodia Sky Striker Genesys Format Feb26
deck_excerpt: Exodia in Genesys format with the best possible consistency.
deck_description:
The following replay exemplifies how to use the deck:

[Link to duelingbook dot com /]

 

replay?id=813757-79325907

 

You can see that the Albion and Sky Striker engines are excellent for keeping Trade-In and Allure of Darkness alive.

 

Going second, basically you always remove the Contract with the Don Thousand and Chicken Game, considering that the opponent will generally have few ways to interact with your spells; these are the easiest for them to negate because they can simply destroy them.

 

With Extra-Foolish Burial you send Infernoid Evil to add Into the Void, and if you have already used the 3 Into the Void, you simply send Garura instead. Tox Boxfish is in the extra deck just in case you're facing a Kewl Tune and it uses Clip's effect.

 

I don't use any Normal Summons because monsters on the field can be easily interrupted by the opponent when you are going second, not to mention they don't help you get 3 spells in the GY quickly to draw a card from the first Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage! activated.

 

In the side deck I put some suggested cards to deal with problematic opponent's monsters:

 

* Gadarla and Lava Golem to deal with omni-negates on the field, or Super Quantal Mech King Great Magnus.

 

* Share the Pain to deal with decks like Mimighoul that set monsters to your field, preventing you from using the effect of Engage.

 

* Dark Ruler No More, Widow Anchor, and Ultimate Slayer to deal with annoying opponent's monsters, and you can even send one of the fusions to the GY and generate draws with that.

 

* Pot of Benevolence just in case I play against a random deck that does hand loops and discards my cards to the GY. This way I can recover the Exodia pieces back to the deck.

 

I usually only put 3 side deck cards in because I need to maintain consistency to win the game with the deck's only win condition.

 

It's an interesting deck for the Genesys format.

deck_name: Duel Monsters 5 Expert 1 - Taikenban (Trial Version) Deck
deck_description:
This is the deck you start with when playing the (sort of rare) trial version of Duel Monsters 5 Expert 1 (which would later be tweaked and released internationally as The Eternal Duelist Soul). While very weak compared to a well-constructed deck, it is notable for having a number of powerful staples, such of Change of Heart, which are not trivial to unlock in the retail release without the use of passwords. The high number of effect monsters is also unusual for a starter deck from a game of this era, as is the existence of a 15 card side deck.

The game ends after only 3-4 games: one game versus one of the 5 "Tier 1" opponents of your choice followed by a best of 3 match versus a random powerful "Tier 4" opponent like Yami Yugi. Hence, it makes sense to show off some of the more powerful and iconic cards during the game's short playtime.

This deck revolves around getting Doomking onto the field as quickly as possible. The setup is simple and consistent: you’ll need Zombie World, then you can either send Doomking directly to the Graveyard or use Glow-Up Bloom to Special Summon him straight to the field.

There are two copies of Doomking in the deck, giving you strong consistency and follow-up plays. From there, you can bring out Orcust, who serves as a solid backrow remover and a reliable defender against major board wipes.

With Doomking and Shinobi Necro, you can Synchro into heavy hitters like Chengying or Arms of Genex.

  • Chengying gains power from all the banished monsters (which synergizes perfectly with Doomking’s banishing effects) and even helps you banish more cards to control the board.

  • Arms of Genex can banish by removing one of your monsters from the Graveyard, giving you two banishes total while also negating the targeted monster’s effect — strong removal and disruption in one package.

To top it all off, the deck runs Royal Decree. While it won’t stop hand traps, it can completely shut down trap-heavy strategies and hits decks like Dark Magician particularly hard.

 

Overall, this deck blends control, banish synergy, and powerful boss monsters into a fun and aggressive strategy.

deck_excerpt: Massive Ojama Deck. Plays Second. King of 1 turn KO.
deck_description: Use Lightning Storm, Dark Ruler, Forbidden Drop, and Trip tactics to protect your attempts to get Blue onto the field. You crash blue into enemy killing him to go get Ojamatch and Ojamagic (repeat this process twice). On the last ojamatch trigger Get red instead of blue filling up your side of the board with ojamas. Use all the draw spells you can (make sure to leave at least 4 creatures on the field. Dont drop to 3 with use of elephant gift. Link spider ojama, than summon another ojama and you can then sac the new ojama to elephant gift and leave the link spider as a 4th monster. Link Summon Saryuja putting all trash on bottom of deck. Use all draw spells as you get them. But the core combo runs off summoning Saryuja 4x times getting the draw 4 3 to bottom effect. You use Tri-Wight to get back the materials to summon the next Saryuja. And then Link Bound to get a 4th saryuja back to the Extra Deck. Oja match collectis dragons to use Allure of Darkness or Sword of Seven draw spells.

deck_excerpt: Skirt Chaser between the Light and Dark
deck_description:
A shamless womanizer, its almost second nature to start flirting when he sees a lady that cathes his eye. He actually used to be rather straight-laced when he was younger, but after being heartbroken by his crush.

Believe himself betrayed, he began to womanize. He is actually somewhat good at flirting, and can even back-up his claims. That said, he's never felt the same zing he felt with his school crush.

There's a part of him who just wants to make up with her, and stop his womanizing tendencies.
Going 2nd with board clears and otk to start, then side in going first support

deck_excerpt: Este  um deck focado em Monstros Mquina, combinando velocidade, consistncia e poder explosivo. A construo mostra uma estratgia agressi
deck_description:
Este é um deck focado em Monstros Máquina, combinando velocidade, consistência e poder explosivo. A construção mostra uma estratégia agressiva que busca colocar múltiplos corpos em campo rapidamente, evoluir para monstros de alto impacto no Extra Deck e pressionar o oponente desde os primeiros turnos.

Estratégia Principal

O baralho gira em torno de:

  • Extensores Máquina que invocam facilmente do campo e da mão

  • Magias de consistência para acelerar as jogadas

  • Combos rápidos que levam a monstros poderosos no Extra Deck

  • Pressão constante com múltiplas invocações por turno

 

A ideia é simples:
Encher o campo → Escalar para monstros fortes → Finalizar rápido.
Testing still - has been bricky, but has good survivability.

Deck that leverages fairy synergies alongside the grind game of the new Branded cards and ability to make the Springans rank 4 to go into Fallen of the White Dragon (White Albaz) pretty much every game. The Herald cards work as great hand traps that also get Ishizu cards into the GY reliably and sometimes on "Turn 0" for additional disruption against most decks. The Ishizu shufflers are very strong here and only cost 1 point each. Shaddoll Construct is a Branded in High Spirits target for fairies. Note that the despia main deck monsters are also fairies and are valid discard targets.

When siding, I mainly consider a few factors. What herald cards are the most effective in the matchup, do I feel the need to have a kaiju when going second, and Shaddoll fusion mini package also for going second. Alba-Lenatus is for dragon-oriented strategies or decks that like to put Secreterion onto the field. I use Twin Twiser over Cosmic Cyclone because of the various discard synergies in the deck.

The deck is currently undefeated against both meta and non-meta over about 15 Bo3 matches; most of which are 2-0 victories (Not that many, I know. But still.). This data may be a bit skewed because I have had people quit the match quite a few times after getting hit by Herald of Orange/Green light on their turn 1 and I discard an Ishizu card for the effect. Or I perform my turn 1 combo and I hit them with Herald of Orange Light on their sole hand trap.

Overall I like the deck a lot. It's challenging to play and feels like it rewards my skill with resource management and the deck in general. I know some people are going to shake their head at the card count being at 50 instead of 40-42, but it does feel just right to me and it makes side decking really easy for me.

TLDR Blind Second White Forest Azamina OTK. Elzette Azamina too good! Goal is to break through all your opponents interaction with board breakers and must answer engine cards before eventually making big 4000 Atk Azamina along with Azamina Silvia to deal double damage for 8000. 

I went Undefeated at my locals with this deck and I have a lot of thoughts.

Firstly, points are tight but there is some flexibility. Chaos Angel was an MVP at my locals but is certainly not mandatory, the points really open up with an extra 20. Consider Fuwa or Nib (Though nib often takes up vital board space) or powerful breakers like dark hole.

Unfortunately the pointed Azamina cards are engine requirements. Elzette Azamina will often use both of her effects, making a synchro to search and then reviving her with toy tank to fuse. Azamina Rcielago can search a Sinful Spoils OR an Azamina card meaning it can grab whatever half you are missing. And Azamina Ilia Sivia gives Azamina cards double damage leading to crazy OTK pushes.

Other techs:

Debtors is great for dodging targeted negation against Subversion or Vengence dragon allowing you to extend in the process.

Shaddoll Fusion is the best breaker in the deck. It can send Eldlitch making it an even more powerful board breaker or send Astellar as potential extension. Don't forget to use Shaddoll Construct's on field effect to send the 2nd shaddoll name from deck.

Ultimate Slayer could be another breaker to help free up extra deck space, especially if monarch continues to be a top deck. That said Slayer is great into every other deck in the format.

Extra Deck: 

Its quite tight obviously. The synchros are slimmed down to the bare minimum, and I consider all the azamina fusions mandatory. Draco Berzerker is a level 8 for synchro climbing with Elzette Azamina. Its also a great breaker and a dark for Chaos Angel. The Ultimate slayer targets and Diamond Dire are the only real flex spots. Diamond Dire helps clear board space that can easily get filled by the toy cards or a stray white forest name, getting just a bit more value out of otherwise blank lvl 4s.

Also, the Side deck is full of cards I am still considering.

Herald of the Abyss, Dark ruler, Swords of Concealing, Twin twister and Double cyclone are all powerful breakers that deal with specific boards. Certainly worth a look depending on the format. Dark ruler especially could be in the main, with the understanding that the white forest end board is an OTK on its own.

Final Bringer has some merit as a breaker in this deck, it can clear zones of unneeded bodies or you can even target your own Rcielago to destroy her and get a search. But compared to other breakers this value can come too late in the turn to matter.

Zombie world and Original sinkeeper are powerful floodgates for Monarch and Radiant Typhoon respectively. Kewl tune can be a hard match up due to the extra deck rip, any suggestions are welcome. I will say, I was never forced to go first by my opponent. I think the white forest endboard is quite scary for any deck to face. 

Chengying is an easy Chaos Angel replacement. Scarlight could replace Diamond Dire or Draco B (though often scarlight will hit your own cards). Immortal Dragon can send Necroworld Banshee or Eldlitch giving you a lvl2 or lvl4 tuner in the process.

Gravity Colapse for going 1st (Duh). 

I love Genesys and will be posting more decks soon. Please post your lists with #YGOGenesys to help support this format!

The announcement of the new DoomZ support in Blazing Dominion has me very excited for the future of the deck. I wouldn't say this is a "solved" list, but the logic behind the ratios make the most sense to me.

For one, the new Pendulum Power Patron is not necessary to the combos the deck has. As a Raiders target, I find it to be worse off the the baby Power Patron since it's search is more restrictive. Plus, searching it off of Amalthe feels worse than just searching Drastea and ending on it with D.O.O.M.D.U.R.G.

Speaking of Amalthe, running it at one feels right. While it is a good card, it's a far worse normal summon compared to Elara, which is just full combo. I tried my best to minimize bricks, which Amalthe could be seen as one. I love the Onomat engine in the deck, but I've seen some lists playing unnecessary cards, like Astraltopia and Onomatopickup.

In more pure builds, these cards are definitely important. But, as a side engine in DoomZ, they aren't needed to hit the ceiling on combos.Since Gogogo Goblindbergh and Dodododo can search for Onomat extenders, you can just use them to make Diactorus, overlay into Graflario, then detatch the Onomat to search. Them, whenever you want to in the combo after resolving Graflario and Raiders summon effects, you can make Gagagaga Girl to search Unbreakable Xyz Barrier for more disruption to strengthen the end board.

Again, I wouldn't say this is a "solved" list for DoomZ. I love seeing other lists for archetypes I like to see what other ideas people have come up with. At the end of the day, I'm just excited to play the deck once Blazing Dominion releases.

traptrix decklist inspired by a recent regional top 8

almost only 3x structure deck + a superpoly package

Fortune Ladies with a Diva Heroes engine, or more, Heroes with a Fortune Lady draw engine.

The main crossover here is Miracle Fusion can be used to banish a Hero and FL Water from the GY to summon Absolute Zero, setting them up to make use of Fortune's Future to draw extra cards and keep fueling the deck.
Otherwise your looking to get out FL Dark and keep recycling your FL Waters for card draw.

We have FL Light with multiple cards to trigger it (Future Visions, Compulse, Skull Lair, Raigeki Break at a push) but thanks to Malicious and Prodigy SS we can easily Tribute out FL Dark if we don't draw any cards for her.

Definitely feel the deck would benefit from a 2nd Skull Lair, or a 2nd Gold Sarc, could maybe cut one Future Visions or Fortune's Future, but deck is still a Work in Progress.



Ignore side deck, just some card ideas.

deck_excerpt: Melodious Archetype Deck for the UCA Format
deck_description: This is a Melodious Deck for Unlocked Core Archetype Format. UCA is a small archetype format played in a few local stores of the Caribean. Decks must consist of exactly 40 cards. At least 23 cards (over 50%) must belong to a single, specific archetype. If a card within your chosen archetype is currently Forbidden by the TCG, it is treated as Limited (1) for your deck. Once you have met the minimum requirement of 23 archetype cards, the remaining slots may be filled with generic support. However, every non-archetype card is Limited to 1 copy per deck. Side Decks are optional, but are limited to cards that must belong to a single, specific archetype. This rules allow players to focus on using the archetype, and still have a sense of competitive gameplay.

deck_excerpt: Mistress of the Skies  Bow Before the Harpie Queen
deck_description: With absolute command over the winds and an unshakable presence, Mai Valentine rules the duel through precision and control. Leading her Harpie flock with elegance and authority, she dismantles her opponent’s strategy piece by piece — clearing the field, outmaneuvering every play, and striking from above when the moment is right. In this deck, every summon is calculated, every gust of wind is deliberate, and every duel is fought on Mai’s terms — because the skies belong to the Harpie Queen.
It does what Marincesses have been doing for years at this point

The initial idea is to Spam with impcantations and make megalith Megalith Notrah Plura  + Megalith Aratron  + Megalith Phul for quick Megalith Bethor  + Vanity's Ruler (the only normal summon on the deck you get it via Cyber Angel Benten  that u can tutor via Impcantation Talismandra , the rest of the creaturesI'm just special summoning) 4 control my opponent's action and make Megalith Phaleg  to finish grinding games. my extradeck is most useless since impcantation monster's locks me from using it, so I just added some generic good cards that some day I will be using when upgrading the deck for now is just Pot of Extravagance fodder. That's my first Yugioh deck ever, studying upgrades, 4 now it's the budgiest that I can afford, later I will upgrade when my budget goes up :)

Don't really have a video, but there are a lot of relays: 996-065-448. This is a standard deck that can get you into Diamond. I haven't gotten into the Masters yet, too busy with life to play this godforsaken game, but here is my deck list to help those wondering souls looking for an average AG deck to play. No clue of its competitive side, but still changing this deck's card support time to time again. Found this one to be much better at having more than one way to get an otk. Learnt from Hardleg Gaming's YT vid on the AG deck he played; sure it's grindy, but nib and droll are always the bane of that deck, so I threw in AG Duel and commander to combat monster effects and kept some of the same format of monsters. I also threw in Dugares to double atk or for an extra 2 draws. TBH, AG doesn't really combo well with any other archetypes. I've played this with Albaz and Feindsmith, and those seemed to work well, but in the end, AG would always have to go first, and any combo making it harder to push those other archetypes onto the field with AG. Maybe some more machine decks in the future can bring more flexibility to the deck, but rn all we have is Dracotail and K9 combos this format, which makes it harder to bait cards out.

- Posted February 23rd, 2026

deck_excerpt: Draw 10+ cards, generate near unlimited resources, and deploy a field full of powerful Dragons!
deck_description:
The kings of 2013 Yugioh meta have returned, only this time it is in GENESYS format! Set up your field, graveyard and hand with a near-limitless Dragon army as you draw 10+ cards with Super Rejuvenation and set up multiple negates/pops! Not only that, you get to reset your opponent's gamestate with Disaster, Dragon Ruler of Apocalypses's field and GY banish! If your opponent manages to survive that and the battlephase, you stack on top of your Disaster an extremely thick 7 material Zeus, enough to wipe your opponent's board three times! 

One of the only floodgates stopping Dragon Rulers from absolutely dominating is essentially gone from the metagame - and that is Droll, too heavily pointed for most decks to consider! The Dragon Ruler pilot still has to watch out for other lingering floodgates such as Dimensional Fissure, Dimension Shifter and Mistaken Arrest. Other than that, Dragon Ruler can usually out-resource, out-muscle and out-grind every GENESYS deck it comes across! 

Shoutout to Joshua Schmidt, whose decklist has inspired this article/video! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oT6vaYtWv-M 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Pumpking's army of card advantage zombies
deck_description:
Join the Domain Format discord server for information on rules and deckbuilding: https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d

(Burst Breath is a stand-in for Deadly Zombie Breath) This is a deck that uses Uni-Zombie as the deck master to search Pumpking the King of Grave Ghosts by sending Glow-Up Bloom from the Deck to the Graveyard, giving us the whole Call of the Haunted engine for it's great interruption and for the repeatable access to Call of the Haunted. Having Card of Safe Return or Vampire Sucker on the field makes all our revival effects draw cards, and we even have Onmoraki which draws a card when it gets revived! The basic gameplan is to send as many Zombies as we can directly from Deck to Grave, get a ton of value from their effects and summon powerful boss monsters from the Extra Deck, especially Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon Lord to revive our Zombies and Skeletal Dragon Felgrand to negate monsters when we revive Zombies!

Keep an eye open Matey, there be machines in these waters...
deck_description:
A fun and modern take on the Plunder Patroll deck, featuring the new Exceptional Schedule as great starter! This list isn't definitive, as I'm not too well versed in the Plunder Patroll Deck, so feel free to use this as a skeleton for your own version.

Plunder Patroll and EARTH Machine don't slot too well together, as Plunder Patroll locks itself into its own archetype through multiple of its own monster effects. You can play around this by simply doing your EARTH Machine and Adventurer combos before proceeding to use Plunder Patroll monsters, however it sucks quite a lot if you draw into either of the two other engines. The Adventurer engine is primarily here due to the size limit: In my testing, Plunder Patroll has difficulties with playing too many Hand Traps, so I dedicated part of the non-engine to a third engine instead. 

In any case, the deck isn't particularly bricky, with the worst Garnets being the EARTH Machine monsters, as well as Urgent Schedule. As long as you don't draw any of those, the deck is able to set up a quite fine field for being Plunder Patroll.
